\par\pard\plain \tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\fi360\sl312\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs26 This study will examine conceptual models presented in two books, the Urantia Book and A Course in Miracles. This book is meant to appeal to students of either one or both. The Urantia Book was published in 1950. A version of The Course in Miracles was published in 1972 by Foundation for Inner Peace. We will not refer to FIP edition. We will use an earlier version as reference, often referred to as the original edition. Both books have unique histories of origin. Both were compiled and published through very different means. Each has developed its own community. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs26 This book is meant to be a reference to parallels of conceptual models within these two books. Keep in mind that the terminology used in the two differ significantly. The Course is more abstract in communicating concepts. It also keeps the terms it uses to a minimum. For instance, the word }{\f1\fs26\i1 knowledge}{\f0\fs26\i0  as referred to in the Course in Miracles refers to a pure spiritual form of knowing based on religious experience that is beyond words, you can only \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93know\u8221\'94 as a result of experience. The Urantia book itself uses the word }{\f1\fs26\i1 knowledge}{\f0\fs26\i0  to cover a wider spectrum of information, including knowledge ranging from the temporal to the eternal perspectives. Additionally, The Course in Miracles uses the term }{\f1\fs26\i1 perception}{\f0\fs26\i0  versus the term }{\f1\fs26\i1 knowledge}{\f0\fs26\i0  to refer to temporal versus eternal points of view. It maintains strict discipline when using these terms. Perception in the Course strictly refers to the animal mind, the egoic mind. The Urantia book uses perception to describe material, semi-spiritual, and spiritual points of view. The Uranita Book also makes an effort to expand on our use of language by using multiple terms to refer to one concept. For instance, it refers to God living within us as the divine monitor, thought adjuster, father fragment, etc. The Course in Miracles uses only the term soul to refer to God living within us. The soul as used in the Course in Miracles is the divine monitor, thought adjuster, and the father fragment. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\i0 In this way the two books use different symantics to relate the same concepts to us. When viewed side by side the concepts communicated can be seen more clearly.   }
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\i0 This book is also an attempt to expand on a conversation between two communities, the Course in Miracles community and the Urantia Book community. Both communities seem to be suspicious of the other to some degree. I hope this book will win over some of the detractors from each community and open a dialog to further the parallel study of each work.  }
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\i0 There is no question that the two books we created by completely separate groups in completely different settings. And yet the concepts communicated in each book compliment each other so thoroughly, it is at least a curiosity as to how they came about in unique ways and have grown separate communities without fully understanding how these two books have so much in common. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\i0 I will consider these two books alone, ruling out all other new age sources of information. I do this not to discredit or minimize other works, but instead to maintain as much clarity as possible. These two books contain enough complexity to sort through. It will be tedious enough without other new age sources to confuse matters. The one source that will be referenced in addition will be the Bible.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\i0 Both have a very independent origin. Both have quite a unique history. Yet when we take a deeper look at the core concepts in each book, we see they are relate to each other  using slightly different language but the parallels are unmistakable. }
